        {
            "id": "ced81956c53c459bbb11a",
            "questionText": "A drone is programmed to deliver a package by flying two distinct legs. First, it flies $!$2.5\\,km$!$ due East and then turns to fly $!$1.8\\,km$!$ due North to avoid an obstacle. Calculate the magnitude of the drone's total displacement from its starting point in $!$km$!$.",
            "imageText": "",
            "steps": [
                {
                    "id": "8622d4d14ac644ea92bcd",
                    "stepText": "Let's start by determining the appropriate formula to calculate the magnitude of a resultant displacement when the two components are perpendicular. Please choose the formula that correctly represents the magnitude of two perpendicular vectors.",
                    "stepText2": "",
                    "stepImage": "",
                    "stepSolveAnswer": [
                        ""
                    ],
                    "stepSolveAnswerUnits": "",
                    "stepConcepts": [
                        "beb69599-eb7b-4356-8d08-85261b652171"
                    ],
                    "options": [
                        {
                            "optionText": "$!$F=\\sqrt{F_x^2+F_y^2}$!$",
                            "optionImage": "",
                            "isCorrect": true
                        },
                        {
                            "optionText": "$!$F=F_x+F_y$!$",
                            "optionImage": "",
                            "isCorrect": false
                        },
                        {
                            "optionText": "$!$F=\\frac{F_x+F_y}{2}$!$",
                            "optionImage": "",
                            "isCorrect": false
                        }
                    ]
                },
                {
                    "id": "f61ba3ab901f451c8e97e",
                    "stepText": "Great! Now, using the selected formula, compute the sum of the squares of the two displacement components. That is, calculate $!$2.5^2$!$ and $!$1.8^2$!$, then add these two results.",
                    "stepText2": "",
                    "stepImage": "",
                    "stepSolveAnswer": [
                        "9.49"
                    ],
                    "stepSolveAnswerUnits": "km^2",
                    "stepConcepts": [
                        "beb69599-eb7b-4356-8d08-85261b652171"
                    ],
                    "options": []
                },
                {
                    "id": "bd163ddef1d54bd88c7e9",
                    "stepText": "Finally, take the square root of the sum obtained in the previous step to get the magnitude of the total displacement.",
                    "stepText2": "",
                    "stepImage": "",
                    "stepSolveAnswer": [
                        "3.08"
                    ],
                    "stepSolveAnswerUnits": "km",
                    "stepConcepts": [
                        "beb69599-eb7b-4356-8d08-85261b652171"
                    ],
                    "options": []
                }
            ]
